<div class="display-inline-block"><button type="button" class="cursor-pointer text-no-underline bg-transparent border-0 padding-0 text-left margin-0 text-normal text-primary" aria-controls="journal_context_menu">J Biomed Inform</button></div>. Author manuscript; available in PMC: 2007 Oct 24.</div>
<div>
<em>Published in final edited form as: </em>J Biomed Inform. 2006 Dec 1;40(3):343–352. doi: <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbi.2006.11.003" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">10.1016/j.jbi.2006.11.003</a>
</div>
<nav id="journal_context_menu" hidden="hidden"><ul class="menu-list font-family-ui" role="menu">
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/search/?term="J%20Biomed%20Inform"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem">Search in PMC</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="J%20Biomed%20Inform"[jour]' lang="en" class="usa-link" role="menuitem">Search in PubMed</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/nlmcatalog?term="J%20Biomed%20Inform"[Title%20Abbreviation]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem">View in NLM Catalog</a></li>
<li role="presentation"><a href='?term="J%20Biomed%20Inform"[jour]' class="usa-link" role="menuitem" data-add-to-search="true">Add to search</a></li>
</ul></nav></section><section class="front-matter"><div class="ameta p font-secondary font-xs">
<hgroup><h1>A statistical methodology for analyzing cooccurrence data from a large sample</h1></hgroup><div class="cg p">
<a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Cao%20H"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id1"><span class="name western">Hui Cao</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id1">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Hui Cao</span>, <span class="degrees">PhD, MD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>a</sup>Department of Biomedical Informatics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div class="p">
<sup>c</sup>Life Sciences &amp; Health Care practice, Deloitte Consulting LLP</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Cao%20H"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Hui Cao</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>a,</sup><sup>c</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Hripcsak%20G"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id2"><span class="name western">George Hripcsak</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id2">
<h3>
<span class="name western">George Hripcsak</span>, <span class="degrees">MD, MS</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>a</sup>Department of Biomedical Informatics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Hripcsak%20G"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">George Hripcsak</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>a,</sup><sup>*</sup>, <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Markatou%20M"[Author]' class="usa-link" aria-describedby="id3"><span class="name western">Marianthi Markatou</span></a><div hidden="hidden" id="id3">
<h3>
<span class="name western">Marianthi Markatou</span>, <span class="degrees">PhD</span>
</h3>
<div class="p">
<sup>b</sup>Department of Biostatistics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div class="p">Find articles by <a href='https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/?term="Markatou%20M"[Author]' class="usa-link"><span class="name western">Marianthi Markatou</span></a>
</div>
</div>
<sup>b</sup>
</div>
<ul class="d-buttons inline-list">
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="aip_a" aria-expanded="false">Author information</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="anp_a" aria-expanded="false">Article notes</button></li>
<li><button class="d-button" aria-controls="clp_a" aria-expanded="false">Copyright and License information</button></li>
</ul>
<div class="d-panels font-secondary-light">
<div id="aip_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none">
<div class="p" id="A1">
<sup>a</sup>Department of Biomedical Informatics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div id="A2">
<sup>b</sup>Department of Biostatistics, Columbia University, New York, NY</div>
<div id="A3">
<sup>c</sup>Life Sciences &amp; Health Care practice, Deloitte Consulting LLP</div>
<div class="author-notes p"><div class="fn" id="FN1">
<sup>✉</sup><p class="display-inline">* Corresponding author, 622 West 168th Street, VC-5, New York, NY 10032., (212) 305-5712 voice;, (212) 305-3302, fax;, <span>hripcsak@columbia.edu</span></p>
</div></div>
</div>
<div id="anp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="notes p"><section id="historyarticle-meta1" class="history"><p>Issue date 2007 Jun.</p></section></div></div>
<div id="clp_a" class="d-panel p" style="display: none"><div class="p"><a href="/about/copyright/" class="usa-link">PMC Copyright notice</a></div></div>
</div>
<div>PMCID: PMC2041889  NIHMSID: NIHMS24299  PMID: <a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17197246/" class="usa-link">17197246</a>
</div>
<div class="ra xbox p" role="complementary" aria-label="Related or updated information about this article"><div>The publisher's version of this article is available at <a href="https://doi.org/10.1016/j.jbi.2006.11.003" class="usa-link usa-link--external" data-ga-action="click_feat_suppl" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">J Biomed Inform</a>
</div></div>
</div></section></section><section aria-label="Article content"><section class="body main-article-body"><section class="abstract" id="abstract1"><h2>Abstract</h2>
<p id="P1">Determining important associations among items in a large database is challenging due to multiple simultaneous hypotheses and the ability to select weak associations that are statistically but not clinically significant. The simple application of the χ<sup>2</sup> test among all possible pairs of items results in mostly inappropriate associations surpassing the traditional (α=.05, χ<sup>2</sup> =3.94) threshold. One can choose a stricter threshold to find stronger associations, but the choice may be arbitrary. We combined the volume test of Diaconis and Efron with a <em>p</em> value plot to select a more rigorous and less arbitrary threshold. The volume test adjusts the p value of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic. A plot of adjusted <em>p</em> values (1-<em>p</em> versus N<sub>p</sub>), where N<sub>p</sub> is the number of test statistics with a <em>p</em> value greater than <em>p</em>, should be linear if there are no true associations. The point where the plot deviates from a line can be used as a threshold. We used linear regression to select the threshold in a reproducible fashion. In one experiment, we found that the method selected a threshold similar to that previously obtained by manually reviewing associations.</p>
<section id="kwd-group1" class="kwd-group"><p><strong>Keywords:</strong> associations, cooccurrence, two-way tables, volume test adjustments, <em>p</em>-value plot, large-scale testing</p></section></section><section id="S1"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">1. Background</h2>
<section id="S2"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">1.1 Motivation</h3>
<p id="P2">In medical practice, information overload is a common problem for physicians who are always confronted with a large amount of clinical data. As they usually have limited time to review the data, information overload may cause information misinterpretation or information neglect, which might result in medical errors in practice. They have needs for accurate abstracts of patients’ conditions, which has triggered increased interests in medical records abstracting/summarization.<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1"><sup>1</sup></a></p>
<p id="P3">An ideal abstract of a patient’s medical condition should reveal the relations between his medical features (<em>e.g.</em>, disease, finding, medication, etc). For example, in an abstract of a patient’s condition, his multiple features are not independent from each other. One problem can be a consequence of another problem, or trigger a subsequent problem. A symptom or a sign can be the manifestation of a disease. A procedure is performed to detect, treat or prevent a disease. A medication is taken to prevent or treat a condition. The features of a patient should be displayed in a way that reflects the relations among them and enables clinicians to receive them as a whole set. Therefore, a sophisticated summarization system needs to be equipped with knowledge of associations between concepts that helps interpret the selected information and present it logically.</p>
<p id="P4">In our previous study, we explored the possibility of using co-occurrence statistics to mine a large corpus (a set of more than 18,000 discharge summaries) to discover associations between diseases and findings.<a href="#R1" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R1"><sup>1</sup></a> The idea for using co-occurrence statistics began with the hypothesis that a disease and an associated finding are more likely to appear together than random combinations of diseases and findings. In our work, we analyze co-occurrence at the level of the report; concepts are said to co-occur if they both occur in the same report. The essence of statistical analysis on the co-occurrence data was to compute the association strength between a pair of a disease and a finding by comparing their expected and observed frequencies. The χ<sup>2</sup> statistic is a classical method that is widely used for this type of analysis. In that study, however, traditional χ<sup>2</sup> statistics rejected most null hypotheses due to the large sample size. For all the 2×2 tables drawn from the same sample, the higher the χ<sup>2</sup> value the greater the magnitude of the dependence. Therefore, we used a heuristic approach in which we manually reviewed the data and selected a high χ<sup>2</sup> cutoff to select the “clinically significant” associations.</p>
<p id="P5">Even though the manually selected cutoff worked well, we were interested in knowing whether it is possible to develop a statistical method to automatically calibrate the χ<sup>2</sup> statistics of the 2×2 tables for selecting the cutoff. This study was conducted to develop such a methodology.</p></section><section id="S3"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">1.2 Challenges in analyzing the cooccurrence data from a large sample</h3>
<p id="P6">We first describe the types of problems we encounter in analyzing co-occurrence data with the aim to calibrate the value of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic. There are 18,432 discharge summaries in the corpus used. These discharge summaries produced 52,197 distinct disease-finding co-occurrence pairs, which are 52,197 different 2 × 2 tables that need to be analyzed. Assume now that one stratifies by disease. Even in this case, there are still a large number of tables that need to be analyzed for each disease. As a simple example, in the hypertension population there are 428 2 × 2 tables. The diabetes mellitus population supplies 729 tables and the depressive disorder population supplies 354 tables.</p>
<p id="P7">From the above description of the data, two fundamental points become obvious. First, there is a large sample size (18,432) that operates. Because of this large sample size the classical χ<sup>2</sup> test for independence in a two-way contingency table often rejects the independence hypothesis, even though the two co-occurring concepts do not have a medically significant association. This is because the classical χ<sup>2</sup> test depends on the sample size: the larger the sample size the higher the power with which to reject the null hypothesis. Recall that for a 2×2 table the chi-square statistic is given by</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD1"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M1" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>n</mn><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="italic">ad</mi><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant="italic">bc</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>,</mo></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P8">where <em>n</em> is the total sample size; <em>a</em>, <em>b</em>, <em>c</em>, <em>d</em> are the observations in cells (1,1), (1,2), (2,1), and (2,2) respectively; <em>r<sub>i</sub></em>, <em>i</em>=1,2 are the row totals; and <em>c<sub>j</sub></em>, <em>j</em>=1,2 are the column totals. For a general <em>r</em>×<em>c</em> table the equation for the χ<sup>2</sup>–statistic is</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD2"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M2" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>=</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>·</mo><mrow><mo stretchy="true">{</mo><mrow><munderover><mo>Σ</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>r</mi></munderover><mi> </mi><mrow><munderover><mo>Σ</mo><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>c</mi></munderover><mi> </mi><mrow><mfrac><mrow><msubsup><mi>F</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">ij</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><msub><mi>c</mi><mi>j</mi></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mrow></mrow><mo stretchy="true">}</mo></mrow><mo>,</mo></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P9">where <em>F<sub>ij</sub></em> is the number of observations in the <em>ij</em><sup>th</sup> cell; <em>r<sub>i</sub></em> is the total of the <em>i</em><sup>th</sup> row; <em>i</em>=1,2,…,<em>r</em>; and <em>c<sub>j</sub></em> is the total of the <em>j</em><sup>th</sup> column, <em>j</em>=1,2,…,<em>c</em>. When the sample size is larger, the test detects smaller deviations from the null hypothesis, which are more likely to be medically insignificant. For example, there may be tiny association between kidney failure and cough (kidney failure patients get cold more often), but this association is not medically interesting. Moreover, when the null hypothesis is rejected, the actual significance level of the χ<sup>2</sup> test, if it can be computed, conveys no additional information about the veracity of the null and alternative hypotheses.</p>
<p id="P10">The second point is that there is a large collection of 2 × 2 tables that need to be analyzed. Because of this large collection of χ<sup>2</sup> tests available (due to the existence of many occurring disease-finding pairs), it is reasonable to think that in some proportion of cases there is a departure from the null hypothesis of independence between the disease and the finding. In this case, interest centers on the question: “which of the cases should be regarded as giving evidence against the null hypothesis?” The goal of the investigation is to identify the cases that deviate from the null hypothesis and the hope is that the number of deviating cases is small. This issue falls within the framework of large-scale simultaneous hypothesis testing introduced by Efron (2004),<a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2"><sup>2</sup></a> which is briefly reviewed in the next section.</p>
<p id="P11">The definition of “large” incorporates two levels. The first level refers to the sample size that is sufficient to create problems in performance of the classical statistical procedures. The second level refers to the pure size of the data as measured perhaps by bytes or by the complexity of a task to be performed on a given size data set.</p>
<p id="P12">In this paper, “large” refers to any value of the sample size that is greater than 100. There are indeed two levels of sample size we deal with in this paper. First, it is the sample size that refers to the number of discharge summaries; in our study this equals 18,432. Next, there is the sample size that refers to the number of χ<sup>2</sup> statistics produced by the number of different co-occurrences. This number is 52,197. The methodology we discuss alleviates the statistical problems, outlined above, that are created by these large samples. As such, for values of the sample size, where sample size refers to the number of co-occurrences being greater than 50, the proposed methodology produces sensible results.</p>
<p id="P13">One limiting factor might be the complexity of the task when considered together with the number of co-occurrences to be tested. In our study, the number of co-occurrences, and hence the number of tests that are simultaneously performed, is 5.2197×10<sup>4</sup> and theoretically our methodology is expected to perform well for any size greater than 50. The computational complexity associated with the method increases as the number of co-occurrences increases and this may be a limiting factor for samples of sizes 10<sup>8</sup> to 10<sup>12</sup>.</p></section><section id="S4"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">1.3 Framework for large-scale simultaneous hypothesis testing</h3>
<p id="P14">Simultaneous inference is an active branch of research in biostatistics. But until very recently “simultaneous inference” meant considering a small number of hypotheses to be tested, perhaps 5~10 hypothesis tests at the same time.<a href="#R2" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R2"><sup>2</sup></a> In biomedical informatics, particularly in the areas of bio-imaging and genomics, the number of tests that need to be considered simultaneously has increased exponentially. It is not uncommon that more than 10,000 tests need to be evaluated at once. Efron (2004) discussed that there are both scientific and statistical differences between large-scale hypothesis testing and small-scale hypothesis testing. A single hypothesis test is most often run with the hope that the test is powerful enough to reject the null hypothesis. However, in large-scale testing researchers are not so much interested in rejecting the null hypothesis as they are in identifying, preferably, a small set of “interesting” cases that deserve further investigation. A requirement in large sample hypothesis testing is that the proportion of interesting cases is small. In fact, the number of true null hypotheses needed to obtain a sensible result with our methods should be sufficiently large so that a straight line can be fitted and a measurable reduction in the R<sup>2</sup> can be obtained. In our study, the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic rejects a large number of null hypotheses despite the fact that the corresponding (disease, finding) pairs are not associated. This is a classical case of “statistical significance” versus “scientific significance”. We aim at calibrating the cutoff point of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic, which is equivalent to identifying a small number of “medically significant” associations from a large collection of pairs of co-occurring diseases and findings. In other words, we are interested in identifying a small number of “scientifically significant” associations.</p>
<p id="P15">In this research, following Efron’s work, we use the terminology “interesting/uninteresting” instead of “significant/non-significant” to indicate the fact that uninteresting cases may be statistically significant.</p></section></section><section id="S5"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">2. Introduction</h2>
<section id="S6"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.1 Assumptions in the analysis of contingency tables</h3>
<p id="P16">If the assumptions which underlie the analysis of contingency tables are violated the results of an analysis based on the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic may be incorrect or misleading. One potential assumption violation is the problem resulting from small expected or observed cell counts. The usual statistic used to analyze associations, <em>i.e.</em> independence in contingency tables, is the χ<sup>2</sup> test. This χ<sup>2</sup> statistic involves using the χ<sup>2</sup> distribution to approximate the underlying exact distribution. This approximation becomes better as the expected cell frequencies grow large and it is inappropriate when those frequencies are very small. Cochran (1954) advised not using the χ<sup>2</sup> test for contingency tables with expected cell frequencies less than 1, or when more than 20% of the contingency table cells have expected frequencies less than 5.<a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3"><sup>3</sup></a> In the 2 × 2 table case, this means all cells should have expected values of 5 or more.</p>
<p id="P17">Sparse tables, that is, tables with small counts, can occur even with large samples. Sparse tables usually contain empty cells, that is, cells with no observations in them. These empty cells, although they allow one to compute the chi-square statistic, can cause sampling distributions of the goodness of fit statistics to be far away from chi-squared. Empty cells also cause problems with the estimation of parameters associated with an r×c table. In our case, we use the continuity correction to account for sparseness and correct the chi-squared statistic.</p>
<p id="P18">In this work, all the 2×2 tables are divided into two categories. The first category contains the tables that satisfy Cochran’s rule (“good” tables), and the second category contains the tables that fail to satisfy Cochran’s rule (“bad” tables). For the bad tables, the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic is corrected for continuity using the formula recommended in Cochran’s paper. For completeness of reporting, the continuity correction of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic was proposed by Yates (1934).<a href="#R3" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R3"><sup>3</sup></a> For <a href="#T1" class="usa-link">Table 1</a>, the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic is corrected using the following formula:</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T1"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 1.</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p>Contingency table</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<thead>
<tr>
<th align="left" rowspan="2" colspan="1">disease</th>
<th align="left" colspan="2" rowspan="1">Finding</th>
<th align="left" rowspan="2" colspan="1">Total</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">+</th>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">-</th>
</tr>
</thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">+</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">a</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">b</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">n<sub>1</sub>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">-</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">c</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">d</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">n<sub>2</sub>
</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Total</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">m<sub>1</sub>
</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">m<sub>2</sub>
</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">N</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><table class="disp-formula p" id="FD3"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M3" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msubsup><mi>χ</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">corr</mi></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mo>∣</mo><mi mathvariant="italic">ad</mi><mo>−</mo><mi mathvariant="italic">bc</mi><mo>∣</mo><mo>−</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mi>n</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mi>n</mi></mrow><mrow><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>m</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>n</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac></mrow></math></td></tr></table></section><section id="S7"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.2 Sampling scheme</h3>
<p id="P19">There are 18,432 discharge summaries in the corpus used to create the disease-finding co-occurrence pairs. Since the total of 18,432 is fixed, the “disease” and “finding” variables are viewed as responses, and interest centers on their joint distribution. This type of sampling with the fixed total is multinomial; that is, the distribution that has generated the data is a multinomial distribution with probability vector π. It can be described as follows:</p>
<p id="P20">Let π<sub>ij</sub> denote the probability that an observation falls in row <em>i</em> and column <em>j</em>, <em>i.e.</em>,</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD4"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M4" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">ij</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P21">where <em>i</em> = 1, 2, <em>j</em> = 1, 2, D denotes “disease” and F denotes “finding”. The corresponding marginals are then,</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD5"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M5" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>+</mo></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>D</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD6"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M6" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>P</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>F</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>j</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>,</mo><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>,</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P22">Then, the hypothesis of independence (no association) between “disease” and “finding” is expressed as</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD7"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M7" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>H</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>:</mo><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">ij</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>+</mo></mrow></msub><mo>×</mo><msub><mi>π</mi><mrow><mo>+</mo><mi>j</mi></mrow></msub></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P23">for all <em>i</em> and <em>j</em>. The multinomial sampling distribution is used in the construction and justification of the volume test adjustments.</p>
<p id="P24">There is another sampling distribution that operates, when one analyzes any disease populations. In those individual disease data, the numbers of observations in the rows of the tables are all fixed throughout the different tables. Denote by r<sub>1</sub> the total of the first row of a 2×2 table and by r<sub>2</sub> the total of the second row. Then, r<sub>1</sub> is the number of patients with the disease and r<sub>2</sub> is the number of patients without the disease in the sample. For example, in the bipolar disorder population the row totals are 248 and 18,184, and in the hypertension population the row totals are 5,821 and 12,711. This type of sampling with one set of marginal totals fixed (in this case, these are the row totals that are fixed) follows what is known as the compound multinomial distribution. In this context, the hypothesis of no association between disease and finding is equivalent to testing homogeneity between the two rows (or columns).</p></section><section id="S8"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.3 Alternative distributions to independence</h3>
<section id="S9"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">2.3.1 Volume test for independence</h4>
<p id="P25">Recall that one of the main disadvantages of the χ<sup>2</sup> test is that with a large sample it rejects the null hypothesis too often. Moreover, after a certain magnitude of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic the associated p-values are all 0, providing no information about the strength of null and alternative hypotheses. In this section, we briefly review an adjustment to the p-value of the χ<sup>2</sup> test proposed by Diaconis and Efron (1985). This adjustment is called a volume test adjustment and, intuitively, can be explained as follows. Look among all possible two way tables and evaluate the proportion of tables that produce a χ<sup>2</sup> statistic that has value smaller or equal to the one produced by the observed table. If this proportion is “small” then the table is “close” to independence, if not then it is far away from it. Therefore, inherent in the computation of the adjustment to the p-value of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic is the idea of interpreting the adjustment ε(χ<sup>2</sup>), as a distance from the surface of independence. Diaconis and Efron (1985) stated that their goal in proposing these adjustments is to extend the usefulness of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic.</p>
<p id="P26">Diaconis and Efron (1985) developed three different formulas for the volume test adjustment. The first formula, which assumes that the total number of observations is fixed, uses the multinomial sampling scheme and is given as follows:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD8"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M8" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>ε</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><mi>π</mi><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy="false">]</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msub><mi>c</mi><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>J</mi></mrow></msub><mi> </mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mi>n</mi><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">IJ</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>/</mo><mi>Γ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="italic">IJ</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="true">(</mo><mtable columnalign="center"><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant="italic">IJ</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">IJ</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo stretchy="true">)</mo></mrow></mfrac></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P27">where n is the total number of observations in the table, I is the number of rows, J indicates the number of columns of the table, D=(I-1)(J-1) indicates the degrees of freedom of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic, <em>S</em>=χ<sup>2</sup>/<em>n</em>, χ<sup>2</sup> is the value of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic, C<sub>I, J</sub> is a constant that depends on the dimension of the table, and Γ(.) is the gamma function. The denominator of ε(χ<sup>2</sup>) is the number of different ways one can draw (IJ-1) items out of a total of (n+IJ-1) items without replacement. It can be computed using the formula:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD9"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M9" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mo stretchy="true">(</mo><mtable columnalign="center"><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant="italic">IJ</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr><mtr><mtd><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">IJ</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mtd></mtr></mtable><mo stretchy="true">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant="italic">IJ</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>n</mi><mo>!</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi mathvariant="italic">IJ</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P28">In the case of a 2×2 table, where I=J=2, the formula of the adjustment is</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD10"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M10" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>ε</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1.85</mn><msup><mi>n</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><msup><mi>S</mi><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>3</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P29">To further understand the volume test adjustment consider the null hypothesis of independence versus the simple alternative that the table is generated by a uniform distribution. Then, the volume test adjustment ε(χ<sup>2</sup>) is the achieved significance level of this test and it can be interpreted as providing the percentage of tables with a χ<sup>2</sup> value that is less than or equal to the observed value. If this percentage is large, the alternative hypothesis that the table is selected uniformly from the set of all possible tables can not be rejected. This is equivalent to saying that the distance of the observed table from the surface of independence is large.</p></section><section id="S10"><h4 class="pmc_sec_title">2.3.2 Conditional and Fixed Margin Volume Tests</h4>
<p id="P30">Diaconis and Efron (1985) derived an alternative formula to the adjustment of the p-value of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic which conditions upon the margins of the table. There are two types of conditioning depending on whether we condition on both row and column margins or just one set of margins, either row or column. When we condition on both sets of margins we call this <em>full conditioning</em> whereas when we condition on just one set of margins we call it <em>partial conditioning</em>. In the analysis of data from sub-populations such as hypertension or bipolar or other disease populations, partial conditioning is recommended by the data as the row margins of the data associated with specific disease populations are fixed.</p>
<p id="P31">When conditioning only on one set of margins, for example rows, the appropriate formula for the conditional (on the row vector r) volume test adjustment for I×J tables is given as follows:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD11"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M11" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>ε</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>∣</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>π</mi><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfrac><mrow><msup><mi>Γ</mi><mi mathvariant="italic">I</mi></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><msup><mi>Γ</mi><mi>J</mi></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>D</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>!</mo><mi>Γ</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="normal">Π</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>I</mi></msubsup><msub><mi>r</mi><mn mathvariant="italic">i</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>J</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msubsup><mi mathvariant="normal">Π</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>I</mi></msubsup><msubsup><mi>r</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>∗</mo></msubsup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>J</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant="italic">IJ</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>J</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P32">where r<sub>i</sub><sup>*</sup> are the components of the vector r*= (1-ω)/I+ ω r, ω =1/(1+(IJ/2n)) and 1 = (1, 1,…, 1); r = (r<sub>1</sub>, r<sub>2</sub>, …, r<sub>I</sub>) are I×1 vectors, and S = (χ<sup>2</sup>/n). When the table is a 2×2 this formula becomes:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD12"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M12" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>ε</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>∣</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mi>π</mi><mn>3</mn></msup><mi>S</mi><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>7.09</mn><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>2</mn><mi>n</mi></mfrac><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mn>2</mn></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msubsup><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn><mo>∗</mo></msubsup><msubsup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn><mo>∗</mo></msubsup><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mfrac><mo>,</mo></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P33">where 
<span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="FD13"><math id="M13" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msubsup><mi>r</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>∗</mo></msubsup></mrow></math></span> are the components of the vector <em>r</em><sup>*</sup> and are given as 
<span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="FD14"><math id="M14" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msubsup><mi>r</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>∗</mo></msubsup><mo>=</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>/</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>n</mi><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></math></span>, <em>i</em>=1,2; <em>r<sub>i</sub></em> are the row marginal probabilities.</p>
<p id="P34">When full conditioning is used the appropriate formula to the volume test adjustment is given by:</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD15"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M15" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>ε</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>∣</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>π</mi><mi>S</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>D</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>J</mi></mrow></msub><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mi>V</mi></mfrac></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD16"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M16" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>C</mi><mrow><mi>I</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>J</mi></mrow></msub><mi> </mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>D</mi><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>!</mo></mrow></mfrac><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>I</mi><msubsup><mi>∏</mi><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>I</mi></msubsup><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>J</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>J</mi><msubsup><mi>∏</mi><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mi>J</mi></msubsup><msub><mi>c</mi><mi>j</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD17"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M17" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>V</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><msup><mi mathvariant="normal">Γ</mi><mi>I</mi></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>J</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow></mfrac><msup><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>J</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi>J</mi></mrow><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>I</mi><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msubsup><mrow><mi>∏</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mrow><mi>I</mi></mrow></msubsup><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mi>g</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>∣</mo><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P35">Because our tables are 2×2 it is possible to compute exactly g(c∣r): The formula that provides g is then given by</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD18"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M18" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>g</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><mi>c</mi><mo>∣</mo><munder accentunder="true"><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy="true">_</mo></munder><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mi>g</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>∣</mo><munder accentunder="true"><mi>r</mi><mo stretchy="true">_</mo></munder><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mrow><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow></mfrac><mo stretchy="false">[</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><munder><mo>Σ</mo><mrow><mo>∣</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>∣</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></munder><mrow><msub><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo></msub></mrow><mo>+</mo><munder><mo>Σ</mo><mrow><mo>∣</mo><mi>A</mi><mo>∣</mo><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></munder><mrow><msub><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo></msub></mrow><mo>+</mo><msub><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo></msub><mo stretchy="false">]</mo><mo>,</mo><msub><mrow><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo></mrow><mo>+</mo></msub><mo>=</mo><mo>max</mo><mo stretchy="false">{</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>,</mo><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>−</mo><mn>1</mn><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo stretchy="false">}</mo><mo>.</mo></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P36">The symbol A represents any subset of the set {1,2}, and ∣A ∣= card(A) indicates the number of elements of the set A. In this case, the first sum is over all sets A that include only one element (that is the sets {1}, {2}), whereas the second sum is over all sets with two elements (this is only the set A={1,2}). Moreover, 
<span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="FD19"><math id="M19" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>A</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mo>Σ</mo><mrow><mi>i</mi><mo>∈</mo><mi>A</mi></mrow></msub><mrow><msub><mi>r</mi><mi>i</mi></msub><mo>,</mo></mrow></mrow></math></span> therefore in the first sum r<sub>A</sub> is either r<sub>1</sub> or r<sub>2</sub>, and in the second sum r<sub>A</sub> = r<sub>1</sub> + r<sub>2</sub>, r<sub>i</sub> = p<sub>i+</sub>, the ratio of observations in row i divided by the total number of observations. In this case, when the table is 2×2 the adjustment simplifies to</p>
<table class="disp-formula p" id="FD20"><tr><td class="formula"><math id="M20" display="block" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mi>ε</mi><mo stretchy="false">(</mo><msup><mi>χ</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>∣</mo><mi>r</mi><mo>,</mo><mi>c</mi><mo stretchy="false">)</mo><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mi>π</mi><mi>S</mi><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>c</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow><mo>!</mo><msup><mrow><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow><mrow><mn>1</mn><mo>/</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi>g</mi><mrow><mo>(</mo><mrow><mi>c</mi><mo>∣</mo><mi>r</mi></mrow><mo>)</mo></mrow></mrow></mfrac><mo>,</mo></mrow></math></td></tr></table>
<p id="P37">where <em>g</em>(<em>c</em>∣<em>r</em>) is given above, <em>r<sub>i</sub></em>, <em>i</em>=1,2 are the row marginals and <em>c<sub>j</sub></em>, <em>j</em>=1,2 are the column marginal probabilities.</p></section></section><section id="S11"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">2.4. <em>P</em>-value plot</h3>
<p id="P38">Recall that our problem is to calibrate the χ<sup>2</sup>. After adjusting the significance level of χ<sup>2</sup> through the appropriate volume test we use the <em>p</em>-value plot to identify an appropriate cutoff point for the χ<sup>2</sup>. The <em>p</em>-value plot, proposed by Schweder and Spjotvoll (1982),<a href="#R6" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R6"><sup>6</sup></a> is a simple graphical procedure, which can estimate approximately the number of true null hypotheses, when a large number of tests are made on the same data. In particular, from the graph it is possible to estimate the number of hypotheses that ought to be “rejected”.</p>
<p id="P39">We now briefly review the <em>p</em>-value plot. The <em>p</em>-value plot is based on the adjusted significance levels of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic. Denote these levels by p<sub>1</sub> , p<sub>2</sub> ,…,p<sub>n</sub>. Let <em>N<sub>p</sub></em> be the number of <em>p</em> values greater than <em>p</em>. The <em>p</em>-value plot is then a plot of the observed values (1 – <em>p</em>, <em>N<sub>p</sub></em>). The left-hand part of the plot should be approximately linear. The points that deviate from linearity correspond to null hypotheses that should be rejected. A straight line is then fitted through the points (1-p<sub>(i)</sub> , N<sub>p(i)</sub>), where p<sub>(i)</sub> is the <em>i</em>th ordered significance probability. This line goes through the point (0,0) because the number of significance probabilities greater than 1 is 0 when the significance probability is approximately 1. The slope of this line is an estimate of the number of true null hypothesis. Often the p-value plot does not show a clear cut break from linearity but rather a gradual bend. To decide on the cutoff point of this graphical device, and hence on the cutoff point of the corresponding χ<sup>2</sup> we first look at the first time at which we observe a decrease in R<sup>2</sup>, and then evaluate this cutoff by computing its sensitivity and specificity and by using bootstrap.</p>
<p id="P40">Therefore, we can summarize the algorithm for the construction of the p-value plot as follows:</p>
<ul id="L1" class="list" style="list-style-type:none">
<li><p id="P41"><span class="text-underline">Step 1</span>: Order the adjusted levels of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic from smallest to largest, that is, <em>p</em>(1), <em>p</em>(2),… <em>p</em>(<em>n</em>), where <em>p</em>(<em>i</em>) denotes the <em>i</em><sup>th</sup> ordered adjustment.</p></li>
<li><p id="P42"><span class="text-underline">Step 2</span>: Construct 1– <em>p</em>(<em>i</em>) and <em>N</em><sub><em>p</em>(<em>i</em>)</sub> where <em>N</em><sub><em>p</em>(<em>i</em>)</sub> is the number of adjusted p-values greater than <em>p</em>(<em>i</em>).</p></li>
<li><p id="P43"><span class="text-underline">Step 3</span>: Plot 1– <em>p</em>(<em>i</em>) versus <em>N</em><sub><em>p</em>(<em>i</em>)</sub>, for all <em>i</em>=1,2,…,<em>n</em>.</p></li>
<li><p id="P44"><span class="text-underline">Step 4</span>: Fit a no-intercept line to the pairs (1– <em>p</em>(<em>i</em>), <em>N</em><sub><em>p</em>(<em>i</em>)</sub>), <em>i</em>=1,2,…,<em>n</em>.</p></li>
</ul></section></section><section id="S12"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">3. Methods</h2>
<p id="P45">The statistical ideas presented in the above sections are not new. However, our innovation lies in the following aspects:</p>
<ol id="L2" class="list" style="list-style-type:decimal">
<li><p id="P46">This is the first attempt to use the presented statistical ideas for the analysis of large scale co-occurrence data.</p></li>
<li><p id="P47">The proposed method allows the simultaneous use of adjusted χ<sup>2	</sup> <em>p</em> values (the adjustment is done via the volume test methodology discussed in Diaconis and Efron’s work (1985)) and a heuristic device, called the <em>p</em>-value plot (discussed by Schweder and Spjotvoll (1982)). The suggestion of combining these two methods is new.</p></li>
<li><p id="P48">The proposed evaluation of the cutoff for the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic in a disease population (because the number of true findings associated with this disease is known), although it is based on well known statistical concepts, such as specificity, sensitivity and bootstrapping, is also new.</p></li>
</ol>
<p id="P49">The overall methodology for analyzing the co-occurrence data is summarized as follows:</p>
<ol id="L3" class="list" style="list-style-type:decimal">
<li><p id="P50">Compute an appropriate volume test adjustment to the significant level of the χ<sup>2</sup> that is based on the value of χ<sup>2</sup> test statistic</p></li>
<li><p id="P51">Use the <em>p</em>-value plot to identify the cutoff to select “clinically significant” associations</p></li>
<li><p id="P52">Evaluate the obtained cutoff</p></li>
</ol>
<p id="P53">The identification, therefore, of the cutoff point is done using the following rule of thumb. We start by fitting no-intercept regression lines to pairs (1–<em>p</em>(<em>i</em>), <em>N</em><sub><em>p</em>(<em>i</em>)</sub>), <em>i</em>=<em>n</em>, <em>n</em>–1, <em>n</em>–2, … and record the coefficient 
<span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="FD21"><math id="M21" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><msubsup><mi>R</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup></mrow></math></span>, of the <em>j</em><sup>th</sup> regression. Construct 
<span xmlns:mml="http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML" id="FD22"><math id="M22" display="inline" overflow="linebreak"><mrow><mo>∣</mo><msubsup><mi>R</mi><mi>j</mi><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>–</mo><msubsup><mi>R</mi><mrow><mi>j</mi><mo>–</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow><mn>2</mn></msubsup><mo>∣</mo></mrow></math></span>; stop when the difference is maximum. We apply this rule to obtain our results recorded in section 4.1. Alternately one can stop fitting no-intercept regression lines to the range 1– <em>p</em><sub>(</sub><em><sub>i</sub></em><sub>)</sub> the first time the value of <em>R</em><sup>2</sup> is smaller than the value obtained in the previous step.</p>
<p id="P54">Evaluation is automatic, in the sense that bootstrapping this value, viewed as a quantile of the chi-squared distribution can provide information about its bias and variance. However, if evaluation of the obtained cutoff is desired using concepts such as sensitivity and specificity, then this type of evaluation needs to be carried out manually.</p>
<p id="P55">In the following section we will analyze co-occurrence data using the above strategy. We will also discuss when it is appropriate to use the various adjustment formulas of the volume test.</p>
<section id="S13"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.1 Analysis of the overall co-occurrence data</h3>
<p id="P56">The volume test is used to adjust the p values of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistics. The approximation for ε(χ<sup>2</sup>) is calculated using the formula mentioned in section 2.3.1. The <em>p</em>-value plot is created by plotting (1-<em>p</em>, N<em><sub>p</sub></em>) where <em>p</em> is the adjusted <em>p</em> value from the volume test and N<em><sub>p</sub></em> is the number of test statistics with a <em>p</em> value greater than <em>p</em>. If the plot does not show a clear-cut break − where the points deviate from a straight line on the right-hand part of the plot − but a gradual bend, we regress (1-<em>p</em>) to N<em><sub>p</sub></em> without an intercept term N<em><sub>p</sub></em> =K(1-<em>p</em>), using increased (0~(1-<em>p</em>))data ranges. We use R-square (R<sup>2</sup>), which is an indicator of goodness of fit for linear regression, to select a range that allows the best fit of linear regression for the right part of the plot. The χ<sup>2</sup> value corresponding to the <em>p</em> value in this range will be selected as a cutoff. Once this cutoff is obtained, we evaluated the disease-finding associations selected by the obtained cutoff using the categories shown in <a href="#T2" class="usa-link">Table 2</a>.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T2"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 2.</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p>The evaluation scale</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<thead><tr>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1"></th>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Interpretation</th>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Example</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">1</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Direct association</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">“gastritis” and “melena”</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">2</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Indirect association</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">“liver cirrhosis” and “hematemesis”</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">3</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Non-association</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">“acute kidney failure” and “diarrhea”</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section></section><section id="S14"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">3.2 Analysis of the co-occurrence data relating to particular diseases</h3>
<p id="P57">After analyzing the overall data, we analyze the co-occurrence data relating to some particular diseases. We are interested in knowing if the method developed can be applied to obtain the cutoff for selecting associated findings for a particular disease. The three disease groups we look into are essential hypertension, bipolar disorder and depressive disorder.</p>
<p id="P58">We extract hypertension-finding, bipolar disorder-finding and depressive disorder-finding co-occurrence data from the overall data, and repeat the procedure described in 3.1.</p>
<p id="P59">As we have mentioned in Section 2.2, the sampling schema in the co-occurrence data related to an individual disease is no longer multinomial distribution assumed for general volume test but product binomial distribution because the row totals in all the 2 × 2 tables are fixed. We suppose conditional volume test that assumes binomial distribution is more appropriate. Therefore, we explore using the conditional volume test (that conditions on both rows and columns) instead of the general volume test to adjust the <em>p</em> values for the three disease data sets. We plot the new adjusted <em>p</em> values.</p>
<p id="P60">Again, if plots do not show a clear-cut break, we regress (1-<em>p</em>) to N<em><sub>p</sub></em> and identify a cutoff from the regression results in the same way described previously. Once a cutoff is obtained, we manually review the three disease data and evaluate the obtained cutoffs using two metrics – sensitivity and specificity.</p></section></section><section id="S15"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">4. Results and discussions</h2>
<section id="S16"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.1 Results of analysis of the overall co-occurrence data</h3>
<p id="P61">Since the <em>p</em>-value plot did not show a clear break (See <a href="#F1" class="usa-link">Figure 1</a>), we regressed (1-<em>p</em>) to N<em><sub>p</sub></em> (N<em><sub>p</sub></em> =K(1-<em>p</em>)), using increased (0~(1-<em>p</em>))data ranges. We can see that when the range of (0~(1-<em>p</em>)) increases from 0−0.8 to 0−0.86, R<sup>2</sup> does not change significantly. When the range changes from 0−0.86 to 0−0.87, an approximately four-fold reduction in R<sup>2</sup> from all previously observed values is detected. (See <a href="#T3" class="usa-link">Table 3</a>). We estimate that the break where the plotted points deviate from the straight line lies within the <em>p</em> values 0.14 and 0.13, which are equivalent to χ<sup>2</sup> values of 110.2 and 100.3. The heuristic cutoff of 100 decided by a manual review in our previous study is close to the lower limit of this obtained range.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F1"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 1.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/b9c6/2041889/a7abd45e014a/nihms24299f1.jpg" loading="lazy" height="548" width="750" alt="Figure 1"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F1/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
