</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Non association</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">98(4.8%)</td>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">128 (5.8%)</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T4/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p id="P63">It is difficult to estimate the sensitivities and specificities associated with the possible cutoffs in the range unless one manually reviews all 52,197 pairs generated from the corpus. An alternative way is by bootstrapping the percentiles corresponding to the obtained cutoffs to get their bias and variance. One can then select the p value whose corresponding percentile has the smallest bias and variances. We bootstrapped the percentiles corresponding to ten p values in the obtained cutoff range. The 95.89<sup>th</sup> percentile that corresponds to the p value of 0.138 and the χ<sup>2</sup> value of 107 has the smallest bias and variance. The χ<sup>2</sup> value 107 seems the best cutoff for the overall co-occurrence data.</p></section><section id="S17"><h3 class="pmc_sec_title">4.2 Results of analysis of the co-occurrence data relating to particular diseases</h3>
<p id="P64">The plots of the p values adjusted by the general volume test for the three disease group are seen in <a href="#F2" class="usa-link">Figure 2</a>, <a href="#F3" class="usa-link">3</a> and <a href="#F4" class="usa-link">4</a>. From the three plots, we can see that the volume test adjustment works well for the hypertension data. Using the same linear regression method described previously, we identified the cutoff for the hypertension group corresponding to <em>p</em> = 0.12 (χ<sup>2</sup> = 95). The volume test did not perform well with either the bipolar disorder or the depressive disorder data. We were not able to identify a cutoff for either data. However, looking at the contingency tables associated with the bipolar disorder and the depressive disorder this performance of the volume test adjustment does not come as a surprise. The bipolar disorder tables have fixed row margins, with a row margin vector of (0.0134, 0.9866); similarly, the depressive disorder tables have fixed row margins and the row vector is (0.099, 0.901). We notice here that the row margins are markedly different from the assumption of uniformity. Therefore, the use of the partial conditioning formula is recommended. The full conditional volume test adjustment also provides sensible results in these cases.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F2"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 2.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/b9c6/2041889/e4d0131d48ff/nihms24299f2.jpg" loading="lazy" height="563" width="750" alt="Figure 2"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F2/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Plot of <em>p</em> values adjusted by the general volume test for the hypertension data</p></figcaption></figure><figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F3"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 3.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/b9c6/2041889/ec8759d6fcf0/nihms24299f3.jpg" loading="lazy" height="617" width="750" alt="Figure 3"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F3/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Plot of <em>p</em> values adjusted by the general volume test for the bipolar disorder data</p></figcaption></figure><figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F4"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 4.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/b9c6/2041889/946f7a6a69bc/nihms24299f4.jpg" loading="lazy" height="612" width="750" alt="Figure 4"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F4/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Plot of <em>p</em> values adjusted by the general volume test for the depressive disorder data</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P65">The plots of the p values adjusted by conditional volume test for the three disease group are seen in <a href="#F5" class="usa-link">Figure 5</a>, <a href="#F6" class="usa-link">6</a> and <a href="#F7" class="usa-link">7</a>. In the hypertension data, the linear regression (N<em><sub>p</sub></em>, 1-<em>p</em>) revealed the cutoff of (<em>p</em>=0.32, χ<sup>2</sup>=92) for the new adjusted <em>p</em> values, which is very close to the one identified previously in the general volume test. Conditional volume test works well with the bipolar disorder data and the depressive disorder data. From the new plots (<a href="#F6" class="usa-link">Figure 6</a> and <a href="#F7" class="usa-link">Figure 7</a>) of the bipolar disorder and depressive disorder data, we can see a relatively clear break where the points deviate from linearity. Using the linear regression, we identified the cutoff of (<em>p</em>=0.8, χ<sup>2</sup>=86) for the bipolar disorder data and the cutoff of (<em>p</em>=0.8, χ<sup>2</sup>=70) for the depressive disorder data.</p>
<figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F5"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 5.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/b9c6/2041889/330d68412fa9/nihms24299f5.jpg" loading="lazy" height="593" width="750" alt="Figure 5"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F5/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Plot of <em>p</em> values from conditional volume tests for the hypertension data</p></figcaption></figure><figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F6"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 6.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/b9c6/2041889/8a7bcccf146d/nihms24299f6.jpg" loading="lazy" height="563" width="750" alt="Figure 6"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F6/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Plot of <em>p</em> values adjusted by conditional volume test for the bipolar disorder data</p></figcaption></figure><figure class="fig xbox font-sm" id="F7"><h4 class="obj_head">Figure 7.</h4>
<p class="img-box line-height-none margin-x-neg-2 tablet:margin-x-0 text-center"><img class="graphic" src="https://cdn.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/blobs/b9c6/2041889/ce8efcd7afa9/nihms24299f7.jpg" loading="lazy" height="601" width="750" alt="Figure 7"></p>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="figure/F7/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div>
<figcaption><p>Plot of <em>p</em> values adjusted by conditional volume test for the bipolar disorder data</p></figcaption></figure><p id="P66">We manually reviewed the three data and evaluated the obtained cutoffs for the three diseases. The results are summarized in <a href="#T5" class="usa-link">Table 5</a>. We can see all the obtained cutoffs achieved a satisfying sensitivity and specificity.</p>
<section class="tw xbox font-sm" id="T5"><h4 class="obj_head">Table 5.</h4>
<div class="caption p"><p>Results of the evaluation of the cutoffs for the three diseases</p></div>
<div class="tbl-box p" tabindex="0"><table class="content" frame="box" rules="all">
<thead><tr>
<th align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Disease Group</th>
<th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">χ<sup>2</sup> Cutoff</th>
<th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Sensitivity</th>
<th align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Specificity</th>
</tr></thead>
<tbody>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Hypertension</td>
<td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">95</td>
<td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">92.6%</td>
<td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">100%</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Bipolar Disorder</td>
<td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">86</td>
<td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">97.0%</td>
<td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">94.1%</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td align="left" rowspan="1" colspan="1">Depressive Disorder</td>
<td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">70</td>
<td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">94.7%</td>
<td align="center" rowspan="1" colspan="1">94.7%</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table></div>
<div class="p text-right font-secondary"><a href="table/T5/" class="usa-link" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">Open in a new tab</a></div></section><p id="P67">After examining the co-occurrence data relating to these three diseases more closely, in addition to the change of sampling schema in these data, we found another reason why the general volume test did not perform well with either the bipolar disorder or the depressive disorder data. It pertains to the fact that in both the bipolar disorder data and the depressive disorder data the 2 × 2 tables are extremely imbalanced while the tables in the hypertension data are moderately imbalanced.</p>
<p id="P68">The above discussion raises the question “under what circumstances the various versions of the volume test adjustments should be used? “ To answer this question note that the alternative hypothesis of uniformity implies that the row and column margins in an I × J table will be approximately uniform, the vector of row margins be approximately (1/I, 1/I,…,1/I) and the vector of column margins be about (1/J, 1/J, …, 1/J) (Diaconis and Efron, 1985). If the margins are non-uniform, as it is the case in the bipolar and depressive disorder disease populations, the volume test adjustment that should be used corresponds to the partial or full conditioning adjustment.</p>
<p id="P69">We can now use this observation to create a rule that measures deviations from uniformity and thus aids in deciding which adjustment should be used. Note that for a 2×2 table the uniform model dictates a+b=n/2, c+d=n/2, a+c=n/2 and b+d=n/2. From these we obtain a=d and b=c. Moreover, the cell counts depend only on a. As the value of a varies this provides different degrees of deviation from uniformity. Using techniques described in Lindsay and Markatou’s work (2006),<a href="#R5" class="usa-link" aria-describedby="R5"><sup>5</sup></a> we can decide how different the table is from uniformity. If we take a=n/4 then the probabilities of each of the four cells in a 2×2 table are approximately equal to 0.25. The average Euclidean distance from this balanced table - in which all cell counts are n/4 - for the bipolar disorder tables is 0.82 with a standard deviation of 0.035, 0.74 for the depressive disorder tables with a standard deviation of 0.024, and 0.55 for the hypertension tables with a standard deviation of 0.020. The data consisting of extremely imbalanced tables, such as the tables in the bipolar disorder data, do not have a big variance in the row and column margins. If we use the general volume test for the data, we underestimate the <em>p</em> value because the general volume test evaluates the proportion of the tables − producing a χ<sup>2</sup> statistic that has value smaller or equal to the one produced by the observed table − in all possible I × J probability tables π rather than the set of tables π having similar margins r and c as the observed table. Conditional volume test is more appropriate to be used in this situation.</p></section></section><section id="S18"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">5. Limitations and other methods</h2>
<p id="P70">The techniques discussed here pertain to the analysis of two-way tables and are not appropriate for addressing three-way and higher dimensional tables. In this paper, although it may be possible to use log-linear models to analyze the data, we have kept modeling to a minimum. This is because the problem we address is that of calibrating the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic because of the tremendous ease of its implementation. The approach of formulating the problem in terms of association models will be the subject of a different paper.</p>
<p id="P71">A variety of methods for estimating the number of true null hypotheses have appeared in the statistics literature. We chose to use the graphical method supplied by the p-value plot because of the extreme ease of implementation and because it is very fast to compute. The adjustment of the χ<sup>2</sup> p-value through the volume test formulas makes direct use of a very easy and very popular statistic, and it addresses directly the problem of its calibration. In a sequel paper we will show the comparison between the proposed method and other methods of direct estimation of the number of true null hypotheses.</p></section><section id="S19"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">6. Conclusion</h2>
<p id="P72">Analysis of the disease-finding co-occurrence data falls within the field of large-scale hypothesis testing. It is very different from single hypothesis testing or small-scale hypothesis testing. The key to the statistical analysis of this kind of data is to identify a small set of “interesting” (“clinically significant”) cases that need further investigation.</p>
<p id="P73">We explored using the volume test of Diaconis and Efron to adjust the <em>p</em> value of the χ<sup>2</sup> statistic in order to calibrate the cutoff of χ<sup>2</sup>. The plot of adjusted <em>p</em> values obtained from volumes tests and linear regression of N<sub>p</sub> onto 1-<em>p</em> allowed the identification of an appropriate cutoff for selecting “interesting” disease-finding associations in the overall co-occurrence data. This developed methodology is extremely easy and easy to implement.</p>
<p id="P74">Even though the volume test worked well for the overall co-occurrence data, one must be careful when applying the same procedure to the co-occurrence data relating to a particular disease due to the change of the assumed sampling schema for two by two tables. Most tables in the co-occurrence data are imbalanced. The general volume test worked well for slightly or moderately imbalanced tables, but did not perform well with severely imbalanced tables, where conditional volume tests should come in.</p></section><section id="S21" class="ack"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Acknowledgments</h2>
<p>This research was funded by National Library of Medicine R01 LM06910 “Discovering and applying knowledge in clinical databases”. Dr. Markatou was funded in addition by National Science Foundation grant DMS-0504957 “Robust statistical distances”.</p></section><section id="fn-group1" class="fn-group"><h2 class="pmc_sec_title">Footnotes</h2>
<div class="fn-group p font-secondary-light font-sm">
